AMERICA’S FEDERAL government will spend hundreds of billions of dollars cancelling student-loan debt—fulfilling a long-standing progressive wish. But while it may be good politics, the policy rationale makes less sense. Too many Nigerian children are sent to beg on the streets by their religious teachers. And celebrating the music and culture of one of Europe’s oldest ethnic minorities. Runtime: 23 min  Listen on: Apple Podcasts | Spotify | Google | Stitcher | TuneIn For full access to print, digital and audio editions of The Economist, subscribe here www.economist.com/intelligenceoffer